{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8c55f467-369f-4821-9034-53fab4475d54","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these locations:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** (most likely):\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_<date>_<machine>.ips`. Recent crashes appear here within seconds.\n\n2. **Console.app** — open it and check **Crash Reports** in the sidebar.\n\n3. **Core dumps** (if enabled):\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited   # enable before running\n   ```\n   Cores land in `/cores/core.<pid>`. Note: SIP may block this on modern macOS.\n\n**For the richest info**, the `.ips` crash report in `DiagnosticReports` is usually your best bet — it includes the faulting thread, stack traces, and signal info without any extra setup.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"41421b81-6272-4c65-b6fd-4862af328e04","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":268,"requestId":"6015:BAB4E:DAD0A9:FE2B1B:69EACA9F"},"id":"dbdc6c99-6eab-481d-bc58-be68a0b04f7d","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:43:03.045Z","parentId":"83570b09-456e-4a82-a833-04bae5cd6e6a"}
